The bug is clear. In `case 1` (inside a quoted string), `args_len` is never incremented — but it **is** incremented in `case 0` when the opening `"` is first seen. So for an argument like `something="test"`, `args_len` includes everything up to and including the opening `"` but misses `test"` (the 5 characters inside and closing the quote). The `args_len` ends up pointing to a truncated buffer that contains `glob=true,something="` — an unclosed string — which the inner parser rejects with "macro arguments parsing error".

Tracing through `.include(glob=true,something="test")`:
1. `glob=true,something=` — counted normally in state 0 (20 chars)
2. Opening `"` — state shifts to 1, but `args_len` is still incremented in state 0 before the switch (char 21)
3. `test"` (5 chars) — in state 1, **not counted** — `args_len` stays at 21
4. `)` — obraces==ebraces, state 99 triggered

Result: inner parser gets `glob=true,something="` (21 bytes) — an unterminated string → parse error.

---

**ROOT CAUSE:** `src/ucl_parser.c:1826–1835` — In the `case 1` branch of `ucl_parse_macro_arguments`, characters inside a double-quoted argument value are scanned with `ucl_chunk_skipc` to advance the position pointer, but `args_len` is never incremented. This causes the length passed to `ucl_parser_add_chunk` (line 1842) to be too short — it only covers up to and including the opening `"` of any quoted value, cutting off the quoted content and leaving an unterminated string literal that the inner parser then rejects.

**LOCAL FIX:** Add `args_len++` inside `case 1`, so every character inside the quoted region (including the closing `"`) is counted:

```c
case 1:
    /* We have quote character, so skip all but quotes */
    if (*p == '"' && *(p - 1) != '\\') {
        state = 0;
    }
    args_len++;          /* count chars inside quoted value */
    if (chunk->remain == 0) {
        goto restore_chunk;
    }
    ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);
    break;
```

**GLOBAL FIX:** Replace the dual-pointer (advance `p`/count `args_len` separately) approach with a single pointer-arithmetic calculation: record the start pointer `c` before the loop and compute `args_len = p - c` once the matching closing `)` is found (before the final `ucl_chunk_skipc` that consumes it). This eliminates the entire class of "forgot to increment the length counter in state N" bugs — any future state added to handle new escape sequences or nested constructs will automatically be included in the length, because the length is derived from pointer difference rather than manually tallied per state.
